{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a9234a09dce3ca67", "type": "tool_result", "content": "{\"query\":\"Codec-ASV neural audio codec speaker verification ICASSP 2025\",\"follow_up_questions\":null,\"answer\":\"Neural audio codecs (NACs) enhance speaker verification by compressing audio signals, showing better performance at low bitrates compared to traditional codecs. They were presented at ICASSP 2025 and continue to evolve for machine perception tasks.\",\"images\":[],\"results\":[{\"url\":\"https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/10888177\",\"title\":\"Codec-ASV: Exploring Neural Audio Codec For Speaker Representation Learning\",\"content\":\"Codec-ASV: Exploring Neural Audio Codec For Speaker Representation Learning | IEEE Conference Publication | IEEE Xplore. Image 1: IEEE Xplore logo - Link to home. Image 2: IEEE logo - Link to IEEE main site homepage. # Codec-ASV: Exploring Neural Audio Codec For Speaker Representation Learning. Among these, Neural Audio Codec (NAC), which serves as a compressed ...Show More. Among these, Neural Audio Codec (NAC), which serves as a compressed form of audio signals, have proven effective in speech AIGC applications. **Published in:**ICASSP 2025 - 2025 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP). [Neural Speech and Audio Coding: Modern AI technology meets traditional codecs [Special Issue On Model-Based and Data-Driven Audio Signal Processing]](https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/10819704 \\\"Neural Speech and Audio Coding: Modern AI technology meets traditional codecs [Special Issue On Model-Based and Data-Driven Audio Signal Processing]\\\")Speech Enhancement Using Continuous Embeddings of Neural Audio CodecLow Frame-rate Speech Codec: a Codec Designed for Fast High-quality Speech LLM Training and Inference.\",\"score\":0.8886914,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/390538079_Codec-ASV_Exploring_Neural_Audio_Codec_For_Speaker_Representation_Learning\",\"title\":\"Exploring Neural Audio Codec For Speaker Representation Learning\",\"content\":\"Codec-ASV: Exploring Neural Audio Codec For Speaker Representation Learning. April 2025. DOI:10.1109/ICASSP49660.2025.10888177. Conference: ICASSP 2025 - 2025\",\"score\":0.8665964,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://www.apsipa.org/proceedings/2025/papers/APSIPA2025_P189.pdf\",\"title\":\"[PDF] Analysis of Speaker Verification Performance Trade-offs with Neural ...\",\"content\":\"Analysis of Speaker Verification Performance Trade-offs with Neural Audio Codec Transmission Nirmalya Mallick Thakur∗and Jia Qi Yip†‡ and Eng Siong Chng† ∗Indian Institute of Science Education and Research, Bhopal † Nanyang Technological University, Singapore ‡ Menlo Research nirmalya23@iiserb.ac.in Abstract—Neural audio codecs (NACs) have made significant advancements in recent years and are rapidly being adopted in many audio processing pipelines. This study investigates the impact of both traditional and neural audio codecs at varying bitrates on three state-of-the-art SV models evaluated on the VoxCeleb1 dataset. Our findings reveal a consistent degradation in SV performance across all models and codecs as bitrates decrease. They outperform Opus by 6-8% at low-bitrates (< 12 kbps) and remain marginally behind at higher bitrates (≈24 kbps), with an EER increase of only 0.4-0.7%. These constraints create a trade-off between transmission bandwidth and performance, where in general, a better audio codec is one that gives higher performance at a given bandwidth.\",\"score\":0.6745014,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.02771\",\"title\":\"[2509.02771] Analysis of Speaker Verification Performance Trade-offs with Neural Audio Codec Transmission\",\"content\":\"# Computer Science > Sound. # Title:Analysis of Speaker Verification Performance Trade-offs with Neural Audio Codec Transmission. | Comments: | Accepted by APSIPA ASC 2025 |. | Subjects: | Sound (cs.SD); Audio and Speech Processing (eess.AS) |. | Cite as: | arXiv:2509.02771 [cs.SD] |. |  | (or  arXiv:2509.02771v1 [cs.SD] for this version) |. |  |  Focus to learn more  arXiv-issued DOI via DataCite |. ## BibTeX formatted citation. # Bibliographic and Citation Tools. # Code, Data and Media Associated with this Article. # Recommenders and Search Tools. # arXivLabs: experimental projects with community collaborators. arXivLabs is a framework that allows collaborators to develop and share new arXiv features directly on our website. Both individuals and organizations that work with arXivLabs have embraced and accepted our values of openness, community, excellence, and user data privacy. arXiv is committed to these values and only works with partners that adhere to them. Have an idea for a project that will add value for arXiv's community?\",\"score\":0.52568597,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://minjekim.com/research-projects/nsac\",\"title\":\"Neural Speech and Audio Coding - Minje Kim's Home\",\"content\":\"# Neural Speech and Audio Coding. ### Neural Speech and Audio Coding: A Research Thread. Over the past several years, my group has been exploring a common question from multiple angles: how should we design neural speech and audio codecs that are both perceptually meaningful and computationally efficient? Neural audio coding aims to compress audio into compact representations that can be faithfully reconstructed, but doing this well requires rethinking loss functions, model structure, quantization, and even the role of source structure in the signal. ##### ACoM: Audio Coding for Machines (WASPAA 2025). ACoM (Audio Coding for Machines) broadens the scope beyond human listening. The project explores representations that remain compact yet maximally useful for machine perception tasks, reflecting the emerging shift from “audio for humans” to audio as a tokenized modality for AI systems. ##### From Hallucination to Articulation: Language Model-Based Losses for Neural Speech Coding (ICASSP 2026). Personalized Neural Speech Codec (PNSC) explores the idea of a speech codec that “knows” your voice—so it can spend its bits and model capacity more efficiently.\",\"score\":0.4177708,\"raw_content\":null}],\"response_time\":1.91,\"request_id\":\"5b136f74-651e-40f4-b5c8-e24fb690a71a\"}", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a67f3bb8bbe29232", "session_id": "74315586-e605-4e80-b1ac-63a94c842af5", "uuid": "c1712a64-4612-486e-8ca8-e59b6bac32e8", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T15:53:37.350Z"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-9d70be36b965619a", "type": "tool_result", "content": "{\"query\":\"DASB discrete audio speech benchmark speaker verification\",\"follow_up_questions\":null,\"answer\":\"DASB is a benchmark for speaker verification using discrete audio tokens. It evaluates various tokenizers for tasks like speaker identification and verification. DASB includes semantic, acoustic, and hybrid tokenizers.\",\"images\":[],\"results\":[{\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2406.14294v4\",\"title\":\"DASB - Discrete Audio and Speech Benchmark\",\"content\":\"# DASB - Discrete Audio and Speech Benchmark. To address this, we introduce the Discrete Audio and Speech Benchmark (DASB), a comprehensive framework for benchmarking discrete audio tokens across speech, general audio, and music domains on a range of discriminative and generative tasks. These tokens are derived using methods such as quantization of self-supervised learning (SSL) models (Polyak et al., 2021; Mousavi et al., 2024; Wells et al., 2022; Chung et al., 2021; Shi et al., 2024a), neural acoustic techniques (codecs)(Kumar et al., 2023; Défossez et al., 2023; Xin et al., 2024; Wu et al., 2024c; Ji et al., 2024; Yang et al., 2024a), or hybrid approaches (Zhang et al., 2024; Du et al., 2023; Défossez et al., 2024; Ye et al., 2025) which enhance codec representations by distilling phonetic. We benchmark a diverse set of discrete audio encoders from all three categories: semantic (Discrete HuBERT, Discrete WavLM, Discrete Wav2Vec2) (Mousavi et al., 2024), acoustic (EnCodec (Défossez et al., 2023), DAC  (Kumar et al., 2023), WavTokenizer (Ji et al., 2024), SQCodec (Yang et al., 2024a)), and hybrid (SpeechTokenizer (Zhang et al., 2024), and Mimi (Défossez et al., 2024)).\",\"score\":0.8332299,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/forum?id=vGWrp0NjaE\",\"title\":\"DASB - Discrete Audio and Speech Benchmark\",\"content\":\"by P Mousavi · Cited by 47 — The benchmark systematically compares semantic, acoustic, and hybrid tokenizers on both discriminative tasks (ASR, speaker verification, emotion recognition,\",\"score\":0.829285,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://poonehmousavi.github.io/DASB-website\",\"title\":\"Documentation for the DASB Benchmark.\",\"content\":\"Discrete Audio and Speech Benchmark DASB is a benchmark for assessing discrete audio tokens across various tasks. It includes different evaluation metrics,\",\"score\":0.7950386,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2406.14294v2\",\"title\":\"Discrete Audio and Speech Benchmark - DASB\",\"content\":\"Speaker Identification/Verification (SID, SV): Speaker Identification involves classifying each utterance by its speaker identity as a multi-\",\"score\":0.77179235,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2024arXiv240614294M/abstract\",\"title\":\"DASB - Discrete Audio and Speech Benchmark - ADS\",\"content\":\"by P Mousavi · 2024 · Cited by 47 — Discrete Audio and Speech Benchmark (DASB), a comprehensive framework for benchmarking discrete audio tokens across speech, general audio, and music domains\",\"score\":0.74785584,\"raw_content\":null}],\"response_time\":1.22,\"request_id\":\"da75181b-86f4-48d9-bb31-fb08b32f25f7\"}", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a67f3bb8bbe29232", "session_id": "74315586-e605-4e80-b1ac-63a94c842af5", "uuid": "f94e2181-1537-45ec-96b3-abd8921bd988", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T15:53:39.267Z"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-98b10a2e7cc53312", "type": "tool_result", "content": "{\"query\":\"knowledge distillation speaker verification embedding 2024 2025\",\"follow_up_questions\":null,\"answer\":\"Knowledge distillation in speaker verification focuses on transferring knowledge from a teacher model to a student model, enhancing performance through relation learning and feature distillation. Recent advancements emphasize non-target speaker knowledge and denoising techniques. The 2024-2025 period saw significant research in this area.\",\"images\":[],\"results\":[{\"url\":\"https://www.isca-archive.org/interspeech_2025/gan25_interspeech.pdf\",\"title\":\"[PDF] Identifying and Distilling Informative Relations for Speaker Verification\",\"content\":\"To address this limitation, rather than simply limiting the knowledge transfer through the one-to-one corre-spondence between the teacher’s and student’s features, we pro-pose forcing the student network to learn the relations between the embeddings of different speakers exhibited by the teacher network. The margin m2 allows knowledge distillation to occur even if the student surpasses the teacher.2 The proposed IDIR framework effectively guides the stu-dent network in learning both intra-speaker compactness and inter-speaker separation. System Row Distillation Type Feature Distillation Loss Metric #Param(M) during inferencing Vox1-O EER%/minDCF Vox1-E EER%/minDCF Vox1-H EER%/minDCF Teacher model WavLM + ECAPA-TDNN 1 – N/A 316.62 0.43/– 0.54/– 1.15/– Student model x-vector 2 – N/A 4.39 1.99/– 1.95/– 3.41/– 3 Embedding (dim=256) Cosine 1.93/0.199 1.86/0.203 3.18/0.289 4 Embedding MSE 1.73/0.173 1.74/0.194 3.02/0.287 5 Embedding Cosine 1.63/0.163 1.72/0.194 3.03/0.292 6 Embedding + Relation (all) Cosine 1.74/0.165 1.76/0.193 3.02/0.288 7 Embedding + Relation (selected) Cosine 1.55/0.171 1.70/0.195 2.94/0.282 8 Logit + Embedding Cosine 1.65/0.175 1.70/0.184 2.94/0.278 9 Logit + Embedding + Relation (selected) Cosine 1.57/0.143 1.65/0.182 2.89/0.274 evaluate the performance of the proposed method.\",\"score\":0.77650476,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1016/j.dsp.2024.104969\",\"title\":\"Lightweight speaker verification with integrated VAD and speech ...\",\"content\":\"Chng, Emphasized non-target speaker knowledge in knowledge distillation for automatic speaker verification, in: ICASSP 2024-2024 IEEE\",\"score\":0.6307082,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=PvJY5hEAAAAJ&hl=zh-CN\",\"title\":\"‪Zezhong Jin‬ - ‪Google 学术搜索‬\",\"content\":\"Denoising student features with diffusion models for knowledge distillation in speaker verification. Z Jin, Y Tu, Z Li, Z Huang, CX Gan, MW Mak. ICASSP 2025-\",\"score\":0.6244086,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://shanmon110.github.io/lz/publications\",\"title\":\"Publications - Dr. Zhe LI\",\"content\":\"... Distilling Informative Relations for Speaker Verification, Proceedings of InterSpeech, Rotterdam, Netherlands, 2025. CCF C; Tiquan Gu, Zhenzhen He, Zhe Li\",\"score\":0.60498303,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://scholar.google.com.hk/citations?user=9dBYelYAAAAJ&hl=nl\",\"title\":\"‪Duc-Tuan Truong‬ - ‪Google Scholar‬\",\"content\":\"Emphasized non-target speaker knowledge in knowledge distillation for automatic speaker verification. DT Truong, R Tao, JQ Yip, KA Lee, ES Chng. ICASSP 2024\",\"score\":0.5769478,\"raw_content\":null}],\"response_time\":1.46,\"request_id\":\"c13db495-8a11-417b-95b7-0b29f8dfa663\"}", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a67f3bb8bbe29232", "session_id": "74315586-e605-4e80-b1ac-63a94c842af5", "uuid": "f771dc9c-7a92-4b2c-a9d0-8b5707762d0c", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T15:53:41.430Z"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8cf90cf75220ceab", "type": "tool_result", "content": "{\"query\":\"VoxCeleb speaker verification SOTA 2025 EER\",\"follow_up_questions\":null,\"answer\":\"The SOTA EER for VoxCeleb speaker verification in 2025 is 0.37 by LAP (h=16) + ASTP. The dataset is used for large-scale speaker recognition and identification. The best models achieve significantly lower error rates than previous works.\",\"images\":[],\"results\":[{\"url\":\"https://www.wizwand.com/sota/speaker-verification-on-voxceleb1-o-cleaned-original\",\"title\":\"SOTA Speaker Verification on VoxCeleb1-O Cleaned (Original) and PapersWithCode | Wizwand\",\"content\":\"| LAP (h=16) + ASTP  2025.12 | 0.37 | - | 0.059 | 0.029 |. | ReDimNet-B4  2024.07 | 0.44 | 0.042 | - | - |. | ECAPA2  2024.07 | 0.44 | 0.041 | - | - |. | MHFA (64 heads)  2025.12 | 0.49 | - | 0.091 | 0.045 |. | ResNet293  2024.07 | 0.53 | 0.057 | - | - |. | DBE (C=512)  2025.12 | 0.63 | - | 0.077 | - |. | NeXt-TDNN (C=256, B=3)  2024.07 | 0.79 | 0.087 | - | - |. | ECAPA-TDNN (C=512)†  2025.12 | 0.85 | - | 0.119 | 0.062 |. | MHFA  2025.12 | 0.89 | - | 0.094 | 0.056 |. | Diff-SV  2026.04 | 2.35 | - | - | - |. | UF-EMA  2026.04 | 2.55 | - | - | - |. | VoiceID  2026.04 | 2.61 | - | - | - |. | NDAL  2026.04 | 2.63 | - | - | - |.\",\"score\":0.7999589,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://www.codesota.com/browse/speech/speaker-verification/voxceleb1-o\",\"title\":\"VoxCeleb1-O — Speaker Verification\",\"content\":\"The original VoxCeleb1 speaker-verification test trials (~37k pairs from 40 speakers). EER (Equal Error Rate, lower=better) is the standard metric. SOTA systems ...Read more\",\"score\":0.6824261,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://github.com/speechbrain/speechbrain/blob/develop/recipes/VoxCeleb/SpeakerRec/README.md\",\"title\":\"speechbrain/recipes/VoxCeleb/SpeakerRec/README.md at develop · speechbrain/speechbrain · GitHub\",\"content\":\"This folder contains scripts for running speaker identification and verification experiments with the VoxCeleb dataset(). To do this, simply run the following command in your terminal:. All the files must be converted in wav files before feeding them is SpeechBrain. 1. Download both Voxceleb1 and Voxceleb2. You can find download instructions here:  Note that for the speaker verification experiments with Voxceleb2 the official split of voxceleb1 is used to compute EER. 2. Convert .m4a to wav Voxceleb2 stores files with the m4a audio format. To use them within SpeechBrain you have to convert all the m4a files into wav files. 1. copy the `voxceleb1/vox1_test_wav.zip` file into the voxceleb2 folder. Note: To prepare the voxceleb1 + voxceleb2 dataset you have to copy and unpack vox1\\\\_dev\\\\_wav.zip for the voxceleb1 dataset. You can use the same script for voxceleb1, voxceleb2, and voxceleb1+2. Run the following command to train speaker embeddings using ECAPA-TDNN. After training the speaker embeddings, it is possible to perform speaker verification using PLDA.\",\"score\":0.6407488,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://hyper.ai/en/sota/tasks/speaker-verification/benchmark/speaker-verification-on-voxceleb\",\"title\":\"Speaker Verification On Voxceleb | SOTA | HyperAI\",\"content\":\"## Command Palette. Search for a command to run... Performance results of various models on this benchmark. ### Metrics. Build the Future of Artificial Intelligence. ### Products. ### Links.\",\"score\":0.42162386,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://www.robots.ox.ac.uk/~vgg/data/voxceleb\",\"title\":\"VoxCeleb\",\"content\":\"A large scale audio-visual dataset of human speech. VoxCeleb is an audio-visual dataset consisting of short clips of human speech, extracted from interview videos uploaded to YouTube. VoxCeleb consists of both audio and video. **Voxceleb: Large-scale speaker verification in the wild**. @Article{Nagrani19, author = \\\"Arsha Nagrani and Joon~Son Chung and Weidi Xie and Andrew Zisserman\\\", title = \\\"Voxceleb: Large-scale speaker verification in the wild\\\", journal = \\\"Computer Science and Language\\\", year = \\\"2019\\\", publisher = \\\"Elsevier\\\", }. The objective of this work is speaker recognition under noisy and unconstrained conditions. First, we introduce a very large-scale audio-visual dataset collected from open source media using a fully automated pipeline. First, we introduce a very large-scale audio-visual speaker recognition dataset collected from open-source media. The models trained on the VoxCeleb2 dataset surpass the performance of previous works on a benchmark dataset by a significant margin. **VoxCeleb: a large-scale speaker identification dataset**. The goal of this paper is to generate a large scale text-independent speaker identification dataset collected ‘in the wild’.\",\"score\":0.38200366,\"raw_content\":null}],\"response_time\":1.28,\"request_id\":\"3f0c4702-adc7-4f08-8443-8d42fc1e4189\"}", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a67f3bb8bbe29232", "session_id": "74315586-e605-4e80-b1ac-63a94c842af5", "uuid": "0e270be1-ee9c-457b-bfe2-9044b3e8dcd1", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T15:53:43.441Z"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-956da3a089e5ce90", "type": "tool_result", "content": "{\"query\":\"neural audio codec discrete tokens speaker recognition 2024 2025\",\"follow_up_questions\":null,\"answer\":\"Neural audio codecs convert audio into discrete tokens, enhancing speaker recognition and various speech applications. Recent models like NDVQ and DualCodec show improved performance. Speaker recognition using these codecs continues to advance in 2024 and 2025.\",\"images\":[],\"results\":[{\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/neural-audio-codec-models\",\"title\":\"Neural Audio Codec Models\",\"content\":\"# Neural Audio Codec Models. * Neural audio codec models are encoder–quantizer–decoder systems that efficiently convert continuous audio signals into discrete token sequences using techniques like RVQ and NDVQ. * They employ adaptive quantization strategies, sophisticated loss functions, and semantic integration to achieve low-bitrate compression while preserving perceptual quality. * These models are pivotal for audio language models, enhancing applications in speech, music, and universal source separation through robust, scalable architectures. A neural audio codec is a trainable encoder–quantizer–decoder pipeline that transforms a continuous audio waveform into a discrete token sequence, enabling both highly efficient compression and powerful generative modeling for speech, music, and general audio. NDVQ outperforms EnCodec at low bitrate across all signal and perceptual metrics (Niu et al., 2024), while DualCodec and FlexiCodec maintain low WER and high MOS at ultra-low token rates (Li et al., 19 May 2025, Li et al., 1 Oct 2025).\",\"score\":0.84767824,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://aclanthology.org/2025.acl-long.1498.pdf\",\"title\":\"Analyzing and Mitigating Inconsistency in Discrete Speech ...\",\"content\":\"2 Analysis on consistency of neural audio codecs In this section, we extract discrete speech tokens from speech segments with and without context using popular neural audio codecs (Défossez et al., 2022; Yang et al., 2023; Zhang et al., 2023b; Du et al., 2024c; Kumar et al., 2024; Ju et al., 2024) to analyze the DRI phenomenon. Table 3 demonstrates that consistency constraint improves the quality of speech generation results across different neural audio codecs and language models, validating the generality of the proposed method. Experimental results indi-cate that our proposed methods can successfully increase the consistency of discrete audio token sequences, thereby enabling the neural codec lan-guage model based on these audio tokens to en-hance the quality of generated speech.\",\"score\":0.7732339,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.10274v3\",\"title\":\"Discrete Audio Tokens: More Than a Survey!\",\"content\":\"Discrete audio tokens are compact representations that aim to preserve perceptual quality, phonetic content, and speaker characteristics while enabling efficient storage and inference, as well as competitive performance across diverse downstream tasks. Driven by these advantages, discrete audio tokens have already been adopted as an alternative to continuous features in a wide range of downstream tasks: automatic speech recognition (Chang et al., 2023; Du et al., 2023), speech-to-speech translation (Popuri et al., 2022; Inaguma et al., 2023; Wu et al., 2023a; Chang et al., 2024), voice conversion (Maimon & Adi, 2023; Wang et al., 2024d), text-to-speech synthesis (Ju et al., 2024; Chen et al., 2025a; Hayashi & Watanabe, 2020), speech enhancement (Wang et al., 2024e; Yang et al., 2024f; Xue et al., 2024), and source separation (Shi et al., 2021c; Erdogan et al., 2023; Mousavi et al., 2024b; Bie et al., 2025; Yip et al., 2024).\",\"score\":0.76951396,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/SLT2024_CodecInvestigation.pdf\",\"title\":\"[PDF] investigating neural audio codecs for speech language model-based\",\"content\":\"Results of AR + NAR models-based speech generation ID Codecs Token rate Continuation generation Cross-speaker generation SIM-O NISQA WER (%) SIM-O NISQA WER (%) CMOS SMOS GT GroundTruth -0.67 3.87 0.96 0.70 3.87 0.96 0.61 4.77 AR model sampling temperature: 1.0 S1 Encodec-official 75 0.43 3.21 4.73 0.47 3.25 3.53 -1.03 4.15 S2 Baseline-16kHz 50 0.46 3.35 10.20 0.48 3.32 11.25 -0.73 4.39 S3 Baseline-Vocos-16kHz 50 0.46 3.52 10.10 0.48 3.53 11.31 -0.70 4.37 S4 DAC-16kHz 50 0.48 3.78 4.97 0.49 3.72 3.31 0.01 4.33 S5 DAC-Vocos-16kHz 50 0.48 3.76 4.95 0.49 3.72 3.28 0.00 4.33 AR model sampling temperature: 0.9 S1a Encodec-official 75 0.44 3.23 3.88 0.47 3.22 3.38 --S2a Baseline-16kHz 50 0.46 3.35 6.94 0.48 3.31 8.52 --S3a Baseline-Vocos-16kHz 50 0.47 3.52 6.97 0.49 3.52 8.63 --S4a DAC-16kHz 50 0.48 3.76 3.08 0.49 3.75 3.03 --S5a DAC-Vocos-16kHz 50 0.48 3.74 3.09 0.50 3.73 2.91 --AR model sampling temperature: 0.8 S1b Encodec-official 75 0.42 3.23 4.59 0.45 3.16 9.80 --S2b Baseline-16kHz 50 0.46 3.35 5.39 0.48 3.23 8.40 --S3b Baseline-Vocos-16kHz 50 0.47 3.54 5.30 0.48 3.46 8.55 --S4b DAC-16kHz 50 0.48 3.74 3.16 0.49 3.69 3.82 --S5b DAC-Vocos-16kHz 50 0.49 3.73 3.17 0.49 3.68 3.89 --worse WER performance compared to other codec settings, despite having similar WER for the reconstruction in Table 2.\",\"score\":0.6680367,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://github.com/ga642381/speech-trident\",\"title\":\"ga642381/speech-trident: Awesome speech/audio LLMs ... - GitHub\",\"content\":\"In this repository, we survey three crucial areas: (1) representation learning, (2) neural codec, and (3) language models that contribute to speech/audio large language models. 1.⚡ **Speech Representation Models:** These models focus on learning structural speech representations, which can then be quantized into discrete speech tokens, often refer to **semantic tokens**. 2.⚡ **Speech Neural Codec Models:** These models are designed to learn speech and audio discrete tokens, often referred to as **acoustic tokens**, while maintaining reconstruction ability and low bitrate. 3.⚡ **Speech Large Language Models:** These models are trained on top of speech and acoustic tokens in a language modeling approach. It provides a comprehensive survey of spoken language models (SLMs), which covers a lot of speech/audio langauge models surveyed in this Speech-Trident project. ## 🔱 Speech/Audio Language Models. | 2025-04 | - | On The Landscape of Spoken Language Models: A Comprehensive Survey | Paper |. | 2025-03 | Baichuan-Audio | Baichuan-Audio: A Unified Framework for End-to-End Speech Interaction | paper |. ## 🔱 Speech/Audio Codec Models.\",\"score\":0.5313802,\"raw_content\":null}],\"response_time\":1.37,\"request_id\":\"cd37850c-a776-47de-affc-6690241834ba\"}", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a67f3bb8bbe29232", "session_id": "74315586-e605-4e80-b1ac-63a94c842af5", "uuid": "63cd41bf-89dc-48e1-b68f-85ea5ff9d765", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T15:53:45.534Z"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a80ca57f103f4cf6", "type": "tool_result", "content": "=== 2010.11567 ===\narxiv_id: '2010.11567'\ntitle: 'AISHELL-3: A Multi-speaker Mandarin TTS Corpus and the Baselines'\nauthors:\n- Yao Shi\n- Hui Bu\n- Xin Xu\n- Shaoji Zhang\n- Ming Li\nyear: 2020\nvenue: ''\ncategories:\n- cs.SD\n- eess.AS\ntopic: speech_dataset\ntags:\n- TTS\n- TTS/功能-多说话人\ncontributions:\n- Introduction of AISHELL-3, a large-scale, publicly available multi-speaker Mandarin\n  speech corpus with high-fidelity recordings, speaker attributes, and manually verified\n\n=== 2110.13900 ===\narxiv_id: '2110.13900'\ntitle: 'WavLM: Large-Scale Self-Supervised Pre-Training for Full Stack Speech Processing'\nauthors:\n- Sanyuan Chen\n- Chengyi Wang\n- Zhengyang Chen\n- Yu Wu\n- Shujie Liu\n- Zhuo Chen\n- Jinyu Li\n- Naoyuki Kanda\n- Takuya Yoshioka\n- Xiong Xiao\n- Jian Wu\n- Long Zhou\n- Shuo Ren\n- Yanmin Qian\n- Yao Qian\n- Jian Wu\n- Michael Zeng\n\n=== 2104.01466 ===\narxiv_id: '2104.01466'\ntitle: ECAPA-TDNN Embeddings for Speaker Diarization\nauthors:\n- Nauman Dawalatabad\n- Mirco Ravanelli\n- François Grondin\n- Jenthe Thienpondt\n- Brecht Desplanques\n- Hwidong Na\nyear: 2021\nvenue: ''\ncategories:\n- eess.AS\ntopic: speech_representation\ntags:\n- ASR\ncontributions:\n- The ECAPA-TDNN model is extended to speaker diarization for the first time, providing\n  robust speaker embeddings for short speaker turns.\n- A powerful data augmentation scheme is introduced that concatenates multiple contaminated", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a67f3bb8bbe29232", "session_id": "74315586-e605-4e80-b1ac-63a94c842af5", "uuid": "2f1b9fae-fd3b-44c2-945a-5598a09f8382", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T15:53:45.571Z"}
