{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1783785229273", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "chatcmpl-tool-bb64709b62e4b72c", "name": "Bash", "input": {"command": "curl -s -X POST 'https://api.tavily.com/search' -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{\"api_key\":\"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\",\"query\":\"arXiv 2607.07579 CFKD speaker verification discrete audio tokens\",\"search_depth\":\"basic\",\"include_answer\":true,\"max_results\":5}' 2>&1", "description": "Tavily search for the specific paper arXiv 2607.07579"}}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a67f3bb8bbe29232", "session_id": "74315586-e605-4e80-b1ac-63a94c842af5", "uuid": "963f9dc8-10c3-4394-a517-5e84e2ee8cac"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b11236e2dea4629c", "type": "tool_result", "content": "2010.11567\n2110.13900\n2104.01466\n---BREAK---\n2207.06389\n2006.04558\n2605.05927\n---BREAK---\n---BREAK---\n2603.27538\n2409.08797\n2601.17124\n2304.09116\n2510.25955\n2507.20091\n2509.24650\n2602.15537\n2510.27688\n2510.16718\n2605.22012\n2408.16532\n2601.19781\n2504.18425\n2509.11425\n2605.10938\n2606.04418\n2512.06609\n2507.22746\n2602.10934\n2508.10711\n2306.06546\n2412.06602\n2604.17852", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a67f3bb8bbe29232", "session_id": "74315586-e605-4e80-b1ac-63a94c842af5", "uuid": "d4b226ef-15b6-4d9f-a25b-570990e64348", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T15:54:15.603Z"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-ba5200c59a2c9390", "type": "tool_result", "content": "{\"query\":\"cross-feature knowledge distillation Fbank codec tokens speaker verification\",\"follow_up_questions\":null,\"answer\":\"Cross-feature knowledge distillation improves speaker verification using neural audio codec tokens by aligning student model embeddings with teacher model embeddings. CFKD enhances performance by leveraging speaker cues in discrete tokens. Optimal lambda for alignment is found to be 40.\",\"images\":[],\"results\":[{\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2607.07579v1\",\"title\":\"Text-Independent Speaker Verification Using Discrete Audio Tokens\",\"content\":\"Neural audio codecs (NACs) enable efficient audio compression and have achieved success in downstream tasks such as speech synthesis. However, their discrete representations consistently underperform traditional spectral features in automatic speaker verification (ASV). We empirically demonstrate that speaker cues are implicitly preserved in discrete tokens but remain underutilized by conventional ASV training paradigms. To address this, we propose a Cross-Feature Knowledge Distillation (CFKD) framework. By guiding the codec-based student to mimic the embedding space of a strong Fbank-based teacher, CFKD provides structured supervision for effective utilization of speaker information in tokens. Experiments on the VoxCeleb benchmarks show that CFKD substantially improves the ASV [...] To better exploit the speaker information encoded in tokens, we propose a Cross-Feature Knowledge Distillation (CFKD) framework. In CFKD, a teacher model with rich, continuous spectral representations provides dense supervision to a token-based student model, guiding it to capture latent speaker-discriminative structures that are otherwise difficult to learn under vanilla cross-entropy-based training. By mimicking the embedding space of a strong Fbank-based teacher, the student model is encouraged to elicit and leverage the inherent speaker cues preserved in neural codec tokens, enabling more effective utilization of discrete representations for ASV.\\n\\nRefer to caption\\nRefer to caption\\n\\n## 2 From Continuous Spectrograms to Discrete Codec Tokens [...] | Setting (λ\\\\lambda) | ECAPA-TDNN1024 | | | |  | ResNet34 | | | |\\n ---  ---  ---  ---  --- |\\n| ID | EER (%) | minDCF | Δ\\\\Delta(%) |  | ID | EER (%) | minDCF | Δ\\\\Delta(%) |\\n| Teacher (Fbank) | E1 | 2.21 | 0.236   | E8 | 2.58 | 0.275 \\n| Student (λ=0\\\\lambda=0, Naive) | E3 | 3.38 | 0.366 | Benchmark |  | E9 | 7.55 | 0.669 | Benchmark |\\n| Student (λ=10\\\\lambda=10) | E4 | 2.51 | 0.290 | 23.3 |  | E10 | 5.07 | 0.491 | 29.8 |\\n| Student (λ=20\\\\lambda=20) | E5 | 2.25 | 0.265 | 30.6 |  | E11 | 4.30 | 0.409 | 41.0 |\\n| Student (λ=40\\\\lambda=40) | E6 | 2.25 | 0.231 | 35.3 |  | E12 | 4.03 | 0.408 | 42.9 |\\n| Student (λ=80\\\\lambda=80) | E7 | 2.30 | 0.256 | 31.1 |  | E13 | 4.23 | 0.428 | 40.0 |\\n\\n### 3.2 Cross-Feature Knowledge Distillation (CFKD)\\n\\n#### 3.2.1 Embedding-level Dense Supervision\",\"score\":0.89302075,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://www.themoonlight.io/tw/review/text-independent-speaker-verification-using-discrete-audio-tokens\",\"title\":\"[論文評述] Text-Independent Speaker Verification Using Discrete Audio Tokens\",\"content\":\"To mitigate this, the authors propose the Cross-Feature Knowledge Distillation (CFKD) framework. This approach employs a two-stream architecture during training:\\n\\nThe student model receives supervision through two objectives: a standard classification loss $L\\\\_{CLS}$ and a distillation loss $L\\\\_{KD}$ that aligns the student’s embedding space with the teacher’s. Given the hyperspherical nature of speaker embeddings, the distillation objective is formulated using cosine similarity to enforce directional alignment:\\n\\n$$L\\\\_{KD} = 1 - \\\\frac{e\\\\_s^\\\\top e\\\\_t}{|e\\\\_s| |e\\\\_t|}$$\\n\\nThe final training objective is a weighted combination of these losses:\\n\\n$$L\\\\_{TOTAL} = L\\\\_{CLS} + \\\\lambda L\\\\_{KD}$$ [...] Moonlight Logo\\nMoonlight Logo\\nMoonlight Logo\\n\\n# [論文評述] Text-Independent Speaker Verification Using Discrete Audio Tokens\\n\\nThis paper addresses the performance degradation observed when applying discrete neural audio codec (NAC) tokens to text-independent Automatic Speaker Verification (ASV). While NACs successfully compress speech, conventional ASV backbones trained on these discrete tokens underperform compared to those using continuous spectral features like Fbanks. The authors demonstrate that this gap is not due to a loss of speaker information, but rather the difficulty of extracting such information from highly compressed, discrete latent spaces using standard cross-entropy-based training.\\n\\n### Core Methodology: Cross-Feature Knowledge Distillation (CFKD) [...] $$L\\\\_{TOTAL} = L\\\\_{CLS} + \\\\lambda L\\\\_{KD}$$\\n\\nWhere $\\\\lambda$ (found to be optimal at 40 in the experiments) regulates the influence of the teacher’s dense geometric guidance.\\n\\n### Key Findings\\n\\nThe study concludes that CFKD serves as a robust paradigm for token-based ASV, validating that discrete representations are viable and efficient alternatives for speaker recognition when paired with appropriate distillation strategies.\\n\\nMoonlight Logo\\n\\nCorca, Inc. / CEO Younghyun Chung / Business Registration Number 271-86-02206\\n\\n6F, 11-8 Teheran-ro 77-gil, Gangnam-gu, Seoul, Republic of Korea, 06159\\n\\nContact 02-6925-6978 E-mail: moonlight@corca.ai\\n\\n© 2026 Corca, Inc. All rights reserved.\",\"score\":0.7738498,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://www.themoonlight.io/en/review/text-independent-speaker-verification-using-discrete-audio-tokens\",\"title\":\"[Literature Review] Text-Independent Speaker Verification Using Discrete Audio Tokens\",\"content\":\"To mitigate this, the authors propose the Cross-Feature Knowledge Distillation (CFKD) framework. This approach employs a two-stream architecture during training:\\n\\nThe student model receives supervision through two objectives: a standard classification loss $L\\\\_{CLS}$ and a distillation loss $L\\\\_{KD}$ that aligns the student’s embedding space with the teacher’s. Given the hyperspherical nature of speaker embeddings, the distillation objective is formulated using cosine similarity to enforce directional alignment:\\n\\n$$L\\\\_{KD} = 1 - \\\\frac{e\\\\_s^\\\\top e\\\\_t}{|e\\\\_s| |e\\\\_t|}$$\\n\\nThe final training objective is a weighted combination of these losses:\\n\\n$$L\\\\_{TOTAL} = L\\\\_{CLS} + \\\\lambda L\\\\_{KD}$$ [...] Moonlight Logo\\nMoonlight Logo\\nMoonlight Logo\\n\\n# [Literature Review] Text-Independent Speaker Verification Using Discrete Audio Tokens\\n\\nThis paper addresses the performance degradation observed when applying discrete neural audio codec (NAC) tokens to text-independent Automatic Speaker Verification (ASV). While NACs successfully compress speech, conventional ASV backbones trained on these discrete tokens underperform compared to those using continuous spectral features like Fbanks. The authors demonstrate that this gap is not due to a loss of speaker information, but rather the difficulty of extracting such information from highly compressed, discrete latent spaces using standard cross-entropy-based training.\\n\\n### Core Methodology: Cross-Feature Knowledge Distillation (CFKD) [...] $$L\\\\_{TOTAL} = L\\\\_{CLS} + \\\\lambda L\\\\_{KD}$$\\n\\nWhere $\\\\lambda$ (found to be optimal at 40 in the experiments) regulates the influence of the teacher’s dense geometric guidance.\\n\\n### Key Findings\\n\\nThe study concludes that CFKD serves as a robust paradigm for token-based ASV, validating that discrete representations are viable and efficient alternatives for speaker recognition when paired with appropriate distillation strategies.\\n\\nMoonlight Logo\\n\\nCorca, Inc. / CEO Younghyun Chung / Business Registration Number 271-86-02206\\n\\n6F, 11-8 Teheran-ro 77-gil, Gangnam-gu, Seoul, Republic of Korea, 06159\\n\\nContact 02-6925-6978 E-mail: moonlight@corca.ai\\n\\n© 2026 Corca, Inc. All rights reserved.\",\"score\":0.76888984,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://hal.science/hal-04886381v1/file/texto_completo.pdf\",\"title\":\"Class token and knowledge distillation for multi-head self- ...\",\"content\":\"Class token and knowledge distillation for multi-head self-attention speaker verification systems. Digital Signal Processing, 2023, 133, pp.103859. ￿10.1016/j.dsp.2022.103859￿. ￿hal-04886381￿ Digital Signal Processing 133 (2023) 103859 Contents lists available at ScienceDirect Digital Signal Processing journal homepage: www.elsevier.com/locate/dsp Class token and knowledge distillation for multi-head self-attention speaker veriﬁcation systems Victoria Mingote ∗, Antonio Miguel, Alfonso Ortega, Eduardo Lleida ViVoLab, Aragón Institute for Engineering Research (I3A), University of Zaragoza, Spain a r t i c l e i n f o a b s t r a c t Article history: Available online 1 December 2022 Keywords: Class token Teacher-student learning Distillation token Speaker veriﬁcation Multi-head [...] Distributed under a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License Class token and knowledge distillation for multi-head self-attention speaker verification systems Victoria Mingote, Antonio Miguel, Alfonso Ortega, Eduardo Lleida To cite this version: Victoria Mingote, Antonio Miguel, Alfonso Ortega, Eduardo Lleida. [...] To summarize, the main contributions are: • We replace the global average pooling mechanism by a learn-able class token to obtain a global utterance descriptor associ-ated to the concept of supervector in speaker veriﬁcation.\\n• We propose a new approach based on a sampling approxima-tion to estimate the class token.\\n• We introduce a teacher-student architecture with an addi-tional token known as distillation token which is combined with the class token to provide robustness to the learned stu-dent model.\",\"score\":0.54753727,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://www.isca-archive.org/interspeech_2023/heo23_interspeech.pdf\",\"title\":\"[PDF] One-Step Knowledge Distillation and Fine-Tuning in Using Large ...\",\"content\":\"Index Terms: Speaker verification, Self-supervised learning model, Knowledge-distillation 1. Introduction Speaker verification (SV) verifies whether the input utterance is vocalized by the target speaker. Most SV studies have employed hand-crafted acoustic features such as spectrogram, Mel spec-trogram, and the Mel-Frequency Cepstral Coefficient (MFCC) as inputs [1, 2]. Recently, in speech signal processing fields, there has been an increasing interest in speech self-supervised learning (SSL) models such as Wav2Vec 2.0 (W2V2) , Hu-BERT , and WavLM  because they have the potential to extract more affluent representation than the hand-craft method [6, 7]. Following this trend, a recent SV work achieved remark-able performance using speech SSL models . [...] One-Step Knowledge Distillation and Fine-Tuning in Using Large Pre-Trained Self-Supervised Learning Models for Speaker Verification Jungwoo Heo∗, Chan-yeong Lim∗, Ju-ho Kim, Hyun-seo Shin, and Ha-Jin Yu† School of Computer Science, University of Seoul jungwoo4021@gmail.com, cksdud585@naver.com, wngh1187@naver.com, gustjtls123@naver.com, hjyu@uos.ac.kr Abstract The application of speech self-supervised learning (SSL) mod-els has achieved remarkable performance in speaker verifica-tion (SV). However, there is a computational cost hurdle in employing them, which makes development and deployment difficult. Several studies have simply compressed SSL mod-els through knowledge distillation (KD) without considering the target task. Consequently, these methods could not extract SV-tailored\",\"score\":0.507544,\"raw_content\":null}],\"response_time\":3.97,\"request_id\":\"c4bf9e20-851d-4294-aa01-25754eb42313\"}", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a67f3bb8bbe29232", "session_id": "74315586-e605-4e80-b1ac-63a94c842af5", "uuid": "55b0af97-cbe6-4e66-8fe7-1c9b92c57076", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T15:54:20.273Z"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-bb64709b62e4b72c", "type": "tool_result", "content": "{\"query\":\"arXiv 2607.07579 CFKD speaker verification discrete audio tokens\",\"follow_up_questions\":null,\"answer\":\"Text-independent speaker verification using discrete audio tokens employs a CFKD framework to improve ASV performance. CFKD enhances codec-based systems to match Fbank-based models. Discrete audio tokens show potential for diverse speech tasks.\",\"images\":[],\"results\":[{\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2607.07579v1\",\"title\":\"Text-Independent Speaker Verification Using Discrete Audio Tokens\",\"content\":\"# Text-Independent Speaker Verification Using Discrete Audio Tokens. To address this, we propose a Cross-Feature Knowledge Distillation (CFKD) framework. By guiding the codec-based student to mimic the embedding space of a strong Fbank-based teacher, CFKD provides structured supervision for effective utilization of speaker information in tokens. Experiments on the VoxCeleb benchmarks show that CFKD substantially improves the ASV performance of codec-based systems, allowing them to approach the accuracy of Fbank-based teacher models and highlighting the potential of discrete audio tokens for diverse speech tasks. In CFKD, a teacher model with rich, continuous spectral representations provides dense supervision to a token-based student model, guiding it to capture latent speaker-discriminative structures that are otherwise difficult to learn under vanilla cross-entropy-based training. By mimicking the embedding space of a strong Fbank-based teacher, the student model is encouraged to elicit and leverage the inherent speaker cues preserved in neural codec tokens, enabling more effective utilization of discrete representations for ASV.\",\"score\":0.90227455,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.07579\",\"title\":\"[2607.07579] Text-Independent Speaker Verification Using Discrete Audio Tokens\",\"content\":\"# Electrical Engineering and Systems Science > Audio and Speech Processing. | Comments: | This paper has been accepted by Interspeech 2026 |. | Subjects: | Audio and Speech Processing (eess.AS) |. | Cite as: | arXiv:2607.07579 [eess.AS] |. |  | (or  arXiv:2607.07579v1 [eess.AS] for this version) |. |  |  Focus to learn more  arXiv-issued DOI via DataCite (pending registration) |. ## Access Paper:. ## BibTeX formatted citation. # Bibliographic and Citation Tools. # Code, Data and Media Associated with this Article. # Recommenders and Search Tools. # arXivLabs: experimental projects with community collaborators. arXivLabs is a framework that allows collaborators to develop and share new arXiv features directly on our website. Both individuals and organizations that work with arXivLabs have embraced and accepted our values of openness, community, excellence, and user data privacy. arXiv is committed to these values and only works with partners that adhere to them. Have an idea for a project that will add value for arXiv's community?\",\"score\":0.8080827,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.07579\",\"title\":\"Text-Independent Speaker Verification Using Discrete ...\",\"content\":\"To better exploit the speaker information encoded in tokens, we propose a Cross-Feature Knowledge Distillation (CFKD) framework. In CFKD, a\",\"score\":0.78709817,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://x.com/AudioAndSpeech/status/2075194887251636569/photo/1\",\"title\":\"Text-Independent Speaker Verification Using Discrete ...\",\"content\":\"Text-Independent Speaker Verification Using Discrete Audio Tokens Zheng Liang, Junjie Li, Kong Aik Lee arxiv.org/abs/2607.07579 [𝚎𝚎𝚜𝚜.𝙰𝚂].\",\"score\":0.75355774,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.10274v3\",\"title\":\"Discrete Audio Tokens: More Than a Survey!\",\"content\":\"Discrete audio tokens are compact representations that aim to preserve perceptual quality, phonetic content, and speaker characteristics while enabling efficient storage and inference, as well as competitive performance across diverse downstream tasks. Driven by these advantages, discrete audio tokens have already been adopted as an alternative to continuous features in a wide range of downstream tasks: automatic speech recognition (Chang et al., 2023; Du et al., 2023), speech-to-speech translation (Popuri et al., 2022; Inaguma et al., 2023; Wu et al., 2023a; Chang et al., 2024), voice conversion (Maimon & Adi, 2023; Wang et al., 2024d), text-to-speech synthesis (Ju et al., 2024; Chen et al., 2025a; Hayashi & Watanabe, 2020), speech enhancement (Wang et al., 2024e; Yang et al., 2024f; Xue et al., 2024), and source separation (Shi et al., 2021c; Erdogan et al., 2023; Mousavi et al., 2024b; Bie et al., 2025; Yip et al., 2024).\",\"score\":0.52393246,\"raw_content\":null}],\"response_time\":1.3,\"request_id\":\"7a048fc5-2c12-4e79-bf1c-c25ba6d7b6e1\"}", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a67f3bb8bbe29232", "session_id": "74315586-e605-4e80-b1ac-63a94c842af5", "uuid": "e51b06ce-b42a-447a-a262-c97fbdb0aeeb", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T15:54:22.301Z"}
