{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a67f3bb8bbe29232", "type": "tool_result", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Here is the consolidated report of all search results.\n\n---\n\n## 1. wiki_query Tool\n\n**STATUS: FAILED.** No `wiki_query` tool exists in this environment. The deferred tool search returned no matches. None of the five requested queries could be executed.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Tavily Web Searches\n\nAll 5 searches SUCCEEDED. Summary of key findings:\n\n### Search 2a: \"Codec-ASV neural audio codec speaker verification ICASSP 2025\" -- SUCCESS\n- **Codec-ASV** (ICASSP 2025, IEEE Xplore DOI 10.1109/ICASSP49660.2025.10888177): Explores NAC for speaker representation learning. This is the most directly relevant prior work.\n- **Thakur et al. (APSIPA 2025, arXiv 2509.02771)**: Analyzes SV performance trade-offs with NAC transmission on VoxCeleb1. Finds consistent degradation at lower bitrates; NACs outperform Opus by 6-8% at low bitrates but remain behind at higher bitrates (EER increase of 0.4-0.7%).\n\n### Search 2b: \"DASB discrete audio speech benchmark speaker verification\" -- SUCCESS\n- **DASB** (arXiv 2406.14294, cited 47 times): Comprehensive benchmark for discrete audio tokens across speech/audio/music. Evaluates semantic (Discrete HuBERT, WavLM, Wav2Vec2), acoustic (EnCodec, DAC, WavTokenizer, SQCodec), and hybrid (SpeechTokenizer, Mimi) tokenizers on speaker verification among other tasks. This is the key benchmark paper for discrete-token ASV.\n\n### Search 2c: \"knowledge distillation speaker verification embedding 2024 2025\" -- SUCCESS\n- **IDIR** (Gan et al., Interspeech 2025): Identifying and Distilling Informative Relations for SV. Proposes relation-based KD between teacher (WavLM + ECAPA-TDNN, 316M params) and student (x-vector, 4.39M params). Best student achieves EER 1.55% on Vox1-O (vs. teacher 0.43%).\n- **Truong et al. (ICASSP 2024)**: Emphasized non-target speaker knowledge in KD for ASV.\n- **Jin et al. (ICASSP 2025)**: Denoising student features with diffusion models for KD in SV.\n- **Mingote et al. (DSP 2023)**: Class token and KD for multi-head self-attention SV systems. Uses distillation tokens.\n- **Heo et al. (Interspeech 2023)**: One-step KD and fine-tuning from SSL models for SV.\n\n### Search 2d: \"VoxCeleb speaker verification SOTA 2025 EER\" -- SUCCESS\n- **Current SOTA on VoxCeleb1-O (Cleaned)**:\n  - LAP (h=16) + ASTP (2025.12): **EER 0.37%**, minDCF 0.059\n  - ReDimNet-B4 (2024.07): EER 0.44%\n  - ECAPA2 (2024.07): EER 0.44%\n  - MHFA (64 heads) (2025.12): EER 0.49%\n  - ResNet293 (2024.07): EER 0.53%\n  - ECAPA-TDNN (C=512) (2025.12): EER 0.85%\n- Source: wizwand.com SOTA leaderboard\n\n### Search 2e: \"neural audio codec discrete tokens speaker recognition 2024 2025\" -- SUCCESS\n- Found a survey \"Discrete Audio Tokens: More Than a Survey!\" (arXiv 2506.10274) covering discrete tokens across ASR, TTS, voice conversion, speech enhancement, etc.\n- NDVQ outperforms EnCodec at low bitrates.\n- DualCodec and FlexiCodec maintain low WER and high MOS at ultra-low token rates.\n- No prior work specifically on cross-feature KD from Fbank to codec tokens was found (other than the target paper itself).\n\n### Search 2f (bonus): \"cross-feature knowledge distillation Fbank codec tokens speaker verification\" -- SUCCESS\n- Found the target paper itself (arXiv 2607.07579, accepted at Interspeech 2026).\n- Found a review/commentary on themoonlight.io summarizing the CFKD framework.\n- Found prior KD-for-SV work (Mingote et al. 2023, Heo et al. 2023) but none involving cross-feature distillation between different input modalities (Fbank teacher to codec-token student).\n\n### Search 2g (bonus): Direct search for arXiv 2607.07579 -- SUCCESS\n- Confirmed: accepted at Interspeech 2026. Authors: Zheng Liang, Junjie Li, Kong Aik Lee.\n- The paper's CFKD results: ECAPA-TDNN1024 with EnCodec tokens achieves EER 2.25% on Vox1-O (vs. Fbank teacher at 2.21%, naive codec student at 3.38%). ResNet34 with CFKD improves from 7.55% to 4.03% EER.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Paper-Wiki (my-paper-wiki) Searches\n\nAll 6 searches executed successfully from `/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/cc-research/my-paper-wiki`.\n\n### `search --concept \"speaker verification\"` -- SUCCESS (3 results)\n- **2010.11567**: AISHELL-3 (multi-speaker Mandarin TTS corpus) -- tangentially related\n- **2110.13900**: WavLM (SSL pre-training for full-stack speech processing) -- relevant as SV backbone\n- **2104.01466**: ECAPA-TDNN for speaker diarization -- directly relevant architecture\n\n### `search --concept \"knowledge distillation speech\"` -- SUCCESS (0 results, empty output)\nNo papers tagged with this concept.\n\n### `search --concept \"knowledge distillation\"` -- SUCCESS (3 results)\n- **2207.06389**, **2006.04558**, **2605.05927** -- would need to check titles for ASV relevance\n\n### `search --concept \"neural audio codec\"` -- SUCCESS (22 results)\nKey papers in the wiki:\n- 2107.03312: SoundStream\n- 2210.13438: High Fidelity Neural Audio Compression (EnCodec)\n- 2306.06546: Improved RVQGAN (DAC)\n- 2301.02111: VALLS (Neural Codec Language Models are Zero-Shot TTS)\n- 2505.13000: DualCodec\n- 2510.00981: FlexiCodec\n- 2604.17852: LLM-Codec\n- 2509.21968: AUV (Audio Universal Vector Quantization)\n- 2603.20638: OmniCodec\n- 2606.04418: CleanCodec\n- And others (TS3-Codec, SpecTokenizer, Q2D2, etc.)\n\n### `search --dataset \"VoxCeleb\"` -- SUCCESS (0 results, empty output)\nNo papers in the wiki are tagged with the VoxCeleb dataset.\n\n### `search --concept \"speaker recognition\"` -- SUCCESS (0 results)\n\n### `search --concept \"discrete tokens\"` -- SUCCESS (24 results)\nOverlaps heavily with the neural audio codec results plus some NLP/speech tokenization papers.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Summary Answers to Key Questions\n\n### What is the current SOTA for VoxCeleb ASV?\nOn **VoxCeleb1-O (Cleaned)**, the SOTA is **LAP (h=16) + ASTP at EER 0.37%** (late 2025). Other strong systems: ReDimNet-B4 (0.44%), ECAPA2 (0.44%), MHFA 64-head (0.49%). Standard ECAPA-TDNN (C=512) sits around 0.85%. The target paper's best result (2.25% EER with ECAPA-TDNN1024 + EnCodec tokens + CFKD) is well below continuous-feature SOTA but represents strong progress for discrete-token ASV.\n\n### What prior work exists on codec-based ASV?\n- **Codec-ASV** (ICASSP 2025): The most directly comparable prior work -- explores NAC for speaker representation learning.\n- **DASB** (2024, cited 47x): Benchmarks multiple discrete tokenizers (EnCodec, DAC, WavTokenizer, etc.) on SV, establishing that discrete tokens underperform continuous features.\n- **Thakur et al.** (APSIPA 2025): Analyzes SV performance degradation from codec transmission at varying bitrates.\n- The DASB benchmark is the primary reference showing the gap between discrete-token and Fbank-based ASV that motivates the target paper.\n\n### What prior work exists on KD for ASV?\nA rich body of work exists:\n- **IDIR** (Interspeech 2025): Relation-based KD for SV (teacher-student with different model sizes, same input features)\n- **Truong et al.** (ICASSP 2024): Non-target speaker KD for ASV\n- **Jin et al.** (ICASSP 2025): Diffusion-based denoising of student features for KD in SV\n- **Mingote et al.** (DSP 2023): Class token + distillation token for MHSA-SV\n- **Heo et al.** (Interspeech 2023): One-step KD from SSL models for SV\n\nAll prior KD-for-SV work involves **same-modality** distillation (teacher and student use the same input type, differing in model size/architecture). No prior work was found that performs **cross-feature** distillation where the teacher and student use fundamentally different input representations (Fbank vs. discrete codec tokens).\n\n### Is the idea of cross-feature KD (Fbank teacher to codec-token student) novel?\n**Yes, it appears novel.** Based on all searches:\n- All prior KD-for-SV work uses same-modality distillation (e.g., large WavLM teacher to small x-vector student, both using waveform/Fbank input).\n- No prior work was found that distills knowledge from a model trained on continuous spectral features (Fbank) to a model trained on discrete neural codec tokens.\n- The specific formulation (cosine similarity-based embedding alignment across different input feature spaces, with a single hyperparameter lambda) is not found in any prior work.\n- The paper itself (accepted at Interspeech 2026) and one commentary on themoonlight.io were the only results for this specific approach."}, {"type": "text", "text": "agentId: ad7dbef42d2efe663 (use SendMessage with to: 'ad7dbef42d2efe663' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 29681\ntool_uses: 19\nduration_ms: 223636</usage>"}]}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "74315586-e605-4e80-b1ac-63a94c842af5", "uuid": "04c4c029-131d-41b3-87fb-bb1bc8e69f0b", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T15:55:55.995Z", "tool_use_result": {"status": "completed", "prompt": "I need you to search for background information to help review a paper about Text-Independent Speaker Verification Using Discrete Audio Tokens (arXiv 2607.07579v1). The paper proposes Cross-Feature Knowledge Distillation (CFKD) to improve ASV performance when using neural audio codec (NAC) discrete tokens instead of Fbank features.\n\nPlease perform the following searches and report ALL results (including failures). Do NOT write any code or modify files. Just search and report findings concisely.\n\n1. Try `wiki_query` tool (if available) with these queries:\n   - query: \"speaker verification SOTA baseline\", tags: [\"speech\", \"ASV\"]\n   - query: \"neural audio codec speaker verification\", tags: [\"speech\", \"codec\"]\n   - query: \"knowledge distillation speaker verification\", tags: [\"speech\", \"KD\"]\n   - query: \"discrete audio tokens speaker recognition\", tags: [\"speech\"]\n   - query: \"EnCodec speaker verification performance\", tags: [\"codec\", \"ASV\"]\n\n2. Use the free-search skill or tavily-search skill to search the web for:\n   - \"Codec-ASV neural audio codec speaker verification ICASSP 2025\"\n   - \"DASB discrete audio speech benchmark speaker verification\"\n   - \"knowledge distillation speaker verification embedding 2024 2025\"\n   - \"VoxCeleb speaker verification SOTA 2025 EER\"\n   - \"neural audio codec discrete tokens speaker recognition 2024 2025\"\n\n3. Also try running from /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/cc-research/my-paper-wiki:\n   - `uv run paper-wiki search --concept \"speaker verification\"`\n   - `uv run paper-wiki search --concept \"knowledge distillation speech\"`\n   - `uv run paper-wiki search --concept \"neural audio codec\"`\n   - `uv run paper-wiki search --dataset \"VoxCeleb\"`\n\nReport all findings concisely. For each search, say whether it succeeded or failed, and summarize the key results. I need to know:\n- What is the current SOTA for VoxCeleb ASV?\n- What prior work exists on codec-based ASV?\n- What prior work exists on KD for ASV?\n- Is the idea of cross-feature KD (Fbank teacher → codec token student) novel?", "agentId": "ad7dbef42d2efe663", "agentType": "general-purpose", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Here is the consolidated report of all search results.\n\n---\n\n## 1. wiki_query Tool\n\n**STATUS: FAILED.** No `wiki_query` tool exists in this environment. The deferred tool search returned no matches. None of the five requested queries could be executed.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Tavily Web Searches\n\nAll 5 searches SUCCEEDED. Summary of key findings:\n\n### Search 2a: \"Codec-ASV neural audio codec speaker verification ICASSP 2025\" -- SUCCESS\n- **Codec-ASV** (ICASSP 2025, IEEE Xplore DOI 10.1109/ICASSP49660.2025.10888177): Explores NAC for speaker representation learning. This is the most directly relevant prior work.\n- **Thakur et al. (APSIPA 2025, arXiv 2509.02771)**: Analyzes SV performance trade-offs with NAC transmission on VoxCeleb1. Finds consistent degradation at lower bitrates; NACs outperform Opus by 6-8% at low bitrates but remain behind at higher bitrates (EER increase of 0.4-0.7%).\n\n### Search 2b: \"DASB discrete audio speech benchmark speaker verification\" -- SUCCESS\n- **DASB** (arXiv 2406.14294, cited 47 times): Comprehensive benchmark for discrete audio tokens across speech/audio/music. Evaluates semantic (Discrete HuBERT, WavLM, Wav2Vec2), acoustic (EnCodec, DAC, WavTokenizer, SQCodec), and hybrid (SpeechTokenizer, Mimi) tokenizers on speaker verification among other tasks. This is the key benchmark paper for discrete-token ASV.\n\n### Search 2c: \"knowledge distillation speaker verification embedding 2024 2025\" -- SUCCESS\n- **IDIR** (Gan et al., Interspeech 2025): Identifying and Distilling Informative Relations for SV. Proposes relation-based KD between teacher (WavLM + ECAPA-TDNN, 316M params) and student (x-vector, 4.39M params). Best student achieves EER 1.55% on Vox1-O (vs. teacher 0.43%).\n- **Truong et al. (ICASSP 2024)**: Emphasized non-target speaker knowledge in KD for ASV.\n- **Jin et al. (ICASSP 2025)**: Denoising student features with diffusion models for KD in SV.\n- **Mingote et al. (DSP 2023)**: Class token and KD for multi-head self-attention SV systems. Uses distillation tokens.\n- **Heo et al. (Interspeech 2023)**: One-step KD and fine-tuning from SSL models for SV.\n\n### Search 2d: \"VoxCeleb speaker verification SOTA 2025 EER\" -- SUCCESS\n- **Current SOTA on VoxCeleb1-O (Cleaned)**:\n  - LAP (h=16) + ASTP (2025.12): **EER 0.37%**, minDCF 0.059\n  - ReDimNet-B4 (2024.07): EER 0.44%\n  - ECAPA2 (2024.07): EER 0.44%\n  - MHFA (64 heads) (2025.12): EER 0.49%\n  - ResNet293 (2024.07): EER 0.53%\n  - ECAPA-TDNN (C=512) (2025.12): EER 0.85%\n- Source: wizwand.com SOTA leaderboard\n\n### Search 2e: \"neural audio codec discrete tokens speaker recognition 2024 2025\" -- SUCCESS\n- Found a survey \"Discrete Audio Tokens: More Than a Survey!\" (arXiv 2506.10274) covering discrete tokens across ASR, TTS, voice conversion, speech enhancement, etc.\n- NDVQ outperforms EnCodec at low bitrates.\n- DualCodec and FlexiCodec maintain low WER and high MOS at ultra-low token rates.\n- No prior work specifically on cross-feature KD from Fbank to codec tokens was found (other than the target paper itself).\n\n### Search 2f (bonus): \"cross-feature knowledge distillation Fbank codec tokens speaker verification\" -- SUCCESS\n- Found the target paper itself (arXiv 2607.07579, accepted at Interspeech 2026).\n- Found a review/commentary on themoonlight.io summarizing the CFKD framework.\n- Found prior KD-for-SV work (Mingote et al. 2023, Heo et al. 2023) but none involving cross-feature distillation between different input modalities (Fbank teacher to codec-token student).\n\n### Search 2g (bonus): Direct search for arXiv 2607.07579 -- SUCCESS\n- Confirmed: accepted at Interspeech 2026. Authors: Zheng Liang, Junjie Li, Kong Aik Lee.\n- The paper's CFKD results: ECAPA-TDNN1024 with EnCodec tokens achieves EER 2.25% on Vox1-O (vs. Fbank teacher at 2.21%, naive codec student at 3.38%). ResNet34 with CFKD improves from 7.55% to 4.03% EER.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Paper-Wiki (my-paper-wiki) Searches\n\nAll 6 searches executed successfully from `/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/cc-research/my-paper-wiki`.\n\n### `search --concept \"speaker verification\"` -- SUCCESS (3 results)\n- **2010.11567**: AISHELL-3 (multi-speaker Mandarin TTS corpus) -- tangentially related\n- **2110.13900**: WavLM (SSL pre-training for full-stack speech processing) -- relevant as SV backbone\n- **2104.01466**: ECAPA-TDNN for speaker diarization -- directly relevant architecture\n\n### `search --concept \"knowledge distillation speech\"` -- SUCCESS (0 results, empty output)\nNo papers tagged with this concept.\n\n### `search --concept \"knowledge distillation\"` -- SUCCESS (3 results)\n- **2207.06389**, **2006.04558**, **2605.05927** -- would need to check titles for ASV relevance\n\n### `search --concept \"neural audio codec\"` -- SUCCESS (22 results)\nKey papers in the wiki:\n- 2107.03312: SoundStream\n- 2210.13438: High Fidelity Neural Audio Compression (EnCodec)\n- 2306.06546: Improved RVQGAN (DAC)\n- 2301.02111: VALLS (Neural Codec Language Models are Zero-Shot TTS)\n- 2505.13000: DualCodec\n- 2510.00981: FlexiCodec\n- 2604.17852: LLM-Codec\n- 2509.21968: AUV (Audio Universal Vector Quantization)\n- 2603.20638: OmniCodec\n- 2606.04418: CleanCodec\n- And others (TS3-Codec, SpecTokenizer, Q2D2, etc.)\n\n### `search --dataset \"VoxCeleb\"` -- SUCCESS (0 results, empty output)\nNo papers in the wiki are tagged with the VoxCeleb dataset.\n\n### `search --concept \"speaker recognition\"` -- SUCCESS (0 results)\n\n### `search --concept \"discrete tokens\"` -- SUCCESS (24 results)\nOverlaps heavily with the neural audio codec results plus some NLP/speech tokenization papers.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Summary Answers to Key Questions\n\n### What is the current SOTA for VoxCeleb ASV?\nOn **VoxCeleb1-O (Cleaned)**, the SOTA is **LAP (h=16) + ASTP at EER 0.37%** (late 2025). Other strong systems: ReDimNet-B4 (0.44%), ECAPA2 (0.44%), MHFA 64-head (0.49%). Standard ECAPA-TDNN (C=512) sits around 0.85%. The target paper's best result (2.25% EER with ECAPA-TDNN1024 + EnCodec tokens + CFKD) is well below continuous-feature SOTA but represents strong progress for discrete-token ASV.\n\n### What prior work exists on codec-based ASV?\n- **Codec-ASV** (ICASSP 2025): The most directly comparable prior work -- explores NAC for speaker representation learning.\n- **DASB** (2024, cited 47x): Benchmarks multiple discrete tokenizers (EnCodec, DAC, WavTokenizer, etc.) on SV, establishing that discrete tokens underperform continuous features.\n- **Thakur et al.** (APSIPA 2025): Analyzes SV performance degradation from codec transmission at varying bitrates.\n- The DASB benchmark is the primary reference showing the gap between discrete-token and Fbank-based ASV that motivates the target paper.\n\n### What prior work exists on KD for ASV?\nA rich body of work exists:\n- **IDIR** (Interspeech 2025): Relation-based KD for SV (teacher-student with different model sizes, same input features)\n- **Truong et al.** (ICASSP 2024): Non-target speaker KD for ASV\n- **Jin et al.** (ICASSP 2025): Diffusion-based denoising of student features for KD in SV\n- **Mingote et al.** (DSP 2023): Class token + distillation token for MHSA-SV\n- **Heo et al.** (Interspeech 2023): One-step KD from SSL models for SV\n\nAll prior KD-for-SV work involves **same-modality** distillation (teacher and student use the same input type, differing in model size/architecture). No prior work was found that performs **cross-feature** distillation where the teacher and student use fundamentally different input representations (Fbank vs. discrete codec tokens).\n\n### Is the idea of cross-feature KD (Fbank teacher to codec-token student) novel?\n**Yes, it appears novel.** Based on all searches:\n- All prior KD-for-SV work uses same-modality distillation (e.g., large WavLM teacher to small x-vector student, both using waveform/Fbank input).\n- No prior work was found that distills knowledge from a model trained on continuous spectral features (Fbank) to a model trained on discrete neural codec tokens.\n- The specific formulation (cosine similarity-based embedding alignment across different input feature spaces, with a single hyperparameter lambda) is not found in any prior work.\n- The paper itself (accepted at Interspeech 2026) and one commentary on themoonlight.io were the only results for this specific approach."}], "totalDurationMs": 223636, "totalTokens": 29681, "totalToolUseCount": 19, "usage": {"input_tokens": 27088, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 2593, "server_tool_use": {"web_search_requests": 0, "web_fetch_requests": 0}, "service_tier": "standard", "cache_creation": {"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens": 0, "eph